  "chunk_index": 31,
  "summary": "Following a funeral, Hastings sits with his daughter, Judith, to discuss her future. Judith reveals her intention to leave England for Africa with Franklin, intending to go as his wife rather than his assistant. This news causes Hastings great distress; he begins to question the true nature of Judith and Franklin, wondering if Judith possessed murderous intent, a thought prompted by the character in *Othello*. He contemplates whether the \"X story\" was a smokescreen created by Poirot to protect Judith or to conceal a tragedy involving the Franklins.\n\nHastings travels to Eastbourne to visit George, Poirot’s former servant. George explains that Poirot had sent him away temporarily to care for his father, though the specific reason remains unknown. George also mentions that Poirot had been wearing a wig due to hair loss. When Hastings presses for more information, George suggests that Poirot may have wanted to hire Curtis, a man who previously worked as an assistant at a mental institution. This leads Hastings to realize that Curtis, rather than a guest at Styles, may have been the mysterious \"X\" all along.\n\nIn a postscript, Hastings notes that he received a sealed package from Poirot’s solicitors four months after the detective's death. The package contains a manuscript in which Poirot explains he is writing to reveal the truth about the \"second Styles Incident.\" Poirot asserts that he has left enough clues for Hastings to discover who killed Norton and warns that the truth regarding the death of Barbara Franklin may be shocking.",
